labels.label: - Pulls object list from specified S3 bucket (exelon-bucket) - Creates flow file for each object (to send to FetchS3Object)
- Inputs records from incoming flow files - Uses INSERT Statement Type into exelon_temperature_table in database - Translates records to SQL for execution

- Controller Services created - CSVReader: parses formatted data - ExelonAvroSchemaRegistry: interprets exelon_temperature_table in database - ExelonPostgresqCon: connects to Exelon postgres database - utilizes GE Enterprise Connect (EC)

labels.label: This flow demonstrates a one-to-one JSON to JSON transformation using Jolt Transformation Language and its complementary processor
This processor allows some HTTP request to enter the flow with all its attributes and content ----------------------------------------------- This processor has been set to only allow GET requets
This processor allows an HTTP response to be sent back to the source of the earlier HTTP request

This processor will prepend data to the current content of the FlowFile --------------------------------------------------- This processor also allows for data to be 'appended to' or 'removed from' the content of a FlowFile ---------------------------------------------------- All of these options are based on a regular expression used to signal what to edit or where in the content of the FlowFile to edit
This processor allows one to do JSON to JSON transformations
This flow will transform JSON using JOLT. It has been used in a POC where we received the original JSON from Salesforce and needed to convert it into a format that Dispatch API understood.
In this use case, we receive XML, convert to SOAP and make a call to SAP PI. We then convert the response back to XML and respond to the client.
